137
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:14,930
True, but this has got to be challenging for him emotionally.

138
00:05:20,090 --> 00:05:21,500
I can't help him.

139
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:22,850
Emotionally.

140
00:05:25,290 --> 00:05:27,570
Excuse me, please.

141
00:05:29,500 --> 00:05:31,200
Excuse me, please.

142
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:34,600
Thank you for keeping me waiting.

143
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:36,670
We doctors are busy, important people.

144
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:38,710
Yeah, we doctors are.

145
00:05:38,710 --> 00:05:41,780
So, pre-op clearance, surgery,

146
00:05:41,780 --> 00:05:43,250
radiation, and chemo.

147
00:05:43,250 --> 00:05:44,370
We're gonna have a lot of fun.

148
00:05:44,370 --> 00:05:46,810
I hope you don't mind if I start with pre-op.

149
00:05:46,810 --> 00:05:49,530
Did you change the policy on pot use?

150
00:05:49,580 --> 00:05:51,930
Are you using again? Should I worry?

151
00:05:51,930 --> 00:05:52,790
I'm clean.

152
00:05:52,790 --> 00:05:54,450
I miss it, but I'm clean.

153
00:05:54,460 --> 00:05:56,050
They test me every week now.

154
00:05:56,060 --> 00:05:56,930
Good.

155
00:06:00,250 --> 00:06:03,470
I think you had me reinstated as your last official act

156
00:06:03,470 --> 00:06:05,530
before they booted you as president

157
00:06:05,530 --> 00:06:07,720
because I am the best oncologist around

158
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:09,620
and you would like to get the best treatment.

159
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:10,650
Yeah.

160
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:13,390
So, I'd like to ensure that the brain,

161
00:06:13,390 --> 00:06:14,890
in this instance, my brain,

162
00:06:14,890 --> 00:06:17,090
stays as dry as possible during surgery,

163
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:18,940
maintain minimal swelling.

164
00:06:18,940 --> 00:06:21,370
I would still like to be able to swing my 9-iron

165
00:06:21,370 --> 00:06:22,250
when we're done here.

166
00:06:22,250 --> 00:06:24,720
Of course, it's also possible that you had me reinstated

167
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:27,340
because you'd like an oncologist who thinks they owe you

168
00:06:27,340 --> 00:06:28,890
and you want to push them around.

169
00:06:31,480 --> 00:06:32,610
Look, Dr. Blaize,

170
00:06:32,610 --> 00:06:34,580
I am, like any other patient,

171
00:06:34,620 --> 00:06:36,520
entitled to have a say in my own treatment,

172
00:06:36,520 --> 00:06:38,510
but unlike any other patient,

173
00:06:38,510 --> 00:06:42,210
I have spent my entire adult life digging into people's brains.

174
00:06:42,210 --> 00:06:44,680
So, if you think I'm gonna sit around and watch,

175
00:06:44,700 --> 00:06:45,800
you're mistaken.

176
00:06:47,530 --> 00:06:49,210
Well, if you think you can operate on yourself,

177
00:06:49,210 --> 00:06:52,040
I'd happily add you to the list of potential surgeons.

178
00:06:53,490 --> 00:06:54,970
Today, you're gonna be waiting.

179
00:06:56,270 --> 00:06:57,160
And waiting.

180
00:06:57,870 --> 00:06:58,740
And waiting.

181
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:00,240
Test, test, test.

182
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:03,530
You've had them all before. I want them again. My versions.

183
00:07:04,450 --> 00:07:05,550
You free all day?

184
00:07:07,310 --> 00:07:08,730
Yeah, sure.

185
00:07:10,590 --> 00:07:11,610
I'm free.

186
00:07:13,880 --> 00:07:14,530
Sir?

187
00:07:17,230 --> 00:07:18,870
We're going to need you to give those back.

188
00:07:18,880 --> 00:07:19,860
What's your name?

189
00:07:20,580 --> 00:07:22,410
I'm Harry. These are my meds.

190
00:07:22,410 --> 00:07:25,300
Those pills are for people with chlamydia, Harry.

191
00:07:25,300 --> 00:07:26,800
No. They're all the same.

192
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:29,550
See, I know better! That's why I have to hide out on the streets.

193
00:07:29,550 --> 00:07:32,370
I had to move next door to Mr. Googly Eyes.

194
00:07:32,370 --> 00:07:33,980
I... I trust him!

195
00:07:34,030 --> 00:07:35,470
He's my friend!

196
00:07:36,260 --> 00:07:37,990
- I trust him. - Okay.

197
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:38,900
- I trust him. - Okay.

198
00:07:38,900 --> 00:07:40,490
- Disorganized thinking, - He's there.

199
00:07:40,490 --> 00:07:42,430
- paranoia, and delusions. - He's always watching me.

200
00:07:42,440 --> 00:07:45,470
I think you have schizophrenia, Harry.

201
00:07:45,620 --> 00:07:47,490
Do you have chlamydia, as well?

202
00:07:48,420 --> 00:07:49,130
Harry?

203
00:07:49,130 --> 00:07:50,300
Harry, are you okay?

204
00:07:57,560 --> 00:07:59,750
That smells very bad.

205
00:08:00,090 --> 00:08:03,120
I get that this is rare. Exciting.

206
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:05,790
The sort of surgery you guys must jump at doing.

207
00:08:05,790 --> 00:08:07,300
I... I just... I want to make sure that we don't...

208
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:08,330
We're not.

209
00:08:09,580 --> 00:08:10,740
I have three months left.

210
00:08:10,740 --> 00:08:12,370
This will give me at least 10 more years.

211
00:08:12,370 --> 00:08:14,790
Should give you 10 more years, yes.

212
00:08:15,840 --> 00:08:17,840
Elliot, I understand your concerns...

213
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:21,690
And Dr. Melendez is one of the best cardiac surgeons around.

214
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:24,970
Dr. Andrews told us all about you

215
00:08:24,970 --> 00:08:27,310
when he convinced me to come here for surgery instead of...

216
00:08:27,310 --> 00:08:29,010
You spoke to Dr. Andrews.

217
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:33,050
And they both already spent half the morning raving to the press.

218
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:36,790
Well, that's... that's very kind.

219
00:08:37,470 --> 00:08:38,740
You spoke to the press?

220
00:08:39,610 --> 00:08:41,450
You spoke to the patient? My patient?

221
00:08:41,720 --> 00:08:43,600
As I explained to Elliot and Melanie,

222
00:08:43,730 --> 00:08:46,010
the press attention is a necessary element

223
00:08:46,010 --> 00:08:47,390
for funding this surgery.

224
00:08:48,190 --> 00:08:49,660
But as you didn't explain to them,

225
00:08:49,660 --> 00:08:51,520
it's simultaneously a vanity project

226
00:08:51,520 --> 00:08:53,360
to create buzz for your new presidency.

227
00:08:53,360 --> 00:08:55,680
As I didn't explain to them,

228
00:08:55,690 --> 00:08:57,520
this surgery can change the way

229
00:08:57,520 --> 00:08:59,870
our entire hospital is perceived.

230
00:09:00,130 --> 00:09:02,220
I'm hoping this buzz, as you put it,

231
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:05,090
will help us establish a surgical center for excellence.

232
00:09:08,420 --> 00:09:09,810
It'll be a nice feather in the cap

233
00:09:09,810 --> 00:09:12,190
for whoever replaces me as Chief of Surgery.

234
00:09:16,930 --> 00:09:17,770
Okay.

235
00:09:17,770 --> 00:09:20,340
Swill your mouth out with alcohol now.

236
00:09:20,340 --> 00:09:21,610
Never said no to that.

237
00:09:21,610 --> 00:09:23,160
You will have to spit.

238
00:09:23,250 --> 00:09:24,600
Oh. Well...

239
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:28,350
Over here.

240
00:09:33,920 --> 00:09:35,840
Are you having trouble with your neck, Harry?

241
00:09:35,980 --> 00:09:37,700
It's stiff.

242
00:09:37,740 --> 00:09:40,870
A stiff neck can be an early indicator of bacterial meningitis.

243
00:09:40,950 --> 00:09:44,280
There are many possible explanations for a stiff neck,

244
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:46,970
most of which are much more likely than bacterial meningitis...

245
00:09:46,970 --> 00:09:49,270
If the abscess has invaded the meninges of his brain,

246
00:09:49,270 --> 00:09:51,450
it could be exacerbating his paranoia.

247
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,520
We need to bring him back to the hospital for a lumbar puncture.

248
00:09:58,090 --> 00:09:58,950
Come on, Shaun.

249
00:09:59,510 --> 00:10:00,810
There's nothing to lose by trying.

250
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,130
I have something to lose.

251
00:10:03,470 --> 00:10:06,360
It's not my last day at St. Bonaventure.

252
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:08,700
Dr. Andrews won't be happy.

253
00:10:10,270 --> 00:10:12,000
Look, it's my responsibility.

254
00:10:12,690 --> 00:10:14,300
If anything happens, I'll take the blame.

255
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:14,950
Okay?

256
00:10:17,350 --> 00:10:18,020
Okay.

257
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:23,320
It's probably best that Jared isn't here on his last day.

258
00:10:26,550 --> 00:10:27,780
It's got to be awkward.

259
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:29,380
I mean, how do you say goodbye to someone

260
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:31,070
who must have meant that much to you?

261
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:36,220
What Jared and I had is over,

262
00:10:36,460 --> 00:10:38,470
and it was never all that much of a big deal, anyway.

263
00:10:39,370 --> 00:10:40,960
You worked with him for over a year.

264
00:10:40,960 --> 00:10:42,910
You were sleeping with him for most of that time.

265
00:10:43,020 --> 00:10:44,000
For me, anyway,

266
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:45,570
you can't sleep with someone and not feel anything.

267
00:10:45,570 --> 00:10:46,880
And for you...

268
00:10:47,120 --> 00:10:49,200
you're way more decent and caring than I am.

269
00:10:56,540 --> 00:10:58,130
Melanie has an aortic aneurysm?

270
00:10:58,130 --> 00:10:59,860
Two hearts beating into that...

271
00:10:59,980 --> 00:11:02,340
Yeah. Not so good.

272
00:11:06,100 --> 00:11:09,130
We could reinforce the dilated aorta with an endovascular stent.

273
00:11:09,300 --> 00:11:11,100
Well, we can't attach the donor heart's aorta

274
00:11:11,100 --> 00:11:12,920
to an aneurysm over a metal tube.

275
00:11:14,550 --> 00:11:16,070
Why not resect the dilated tissue

276
00:11:16,070 --> 00:11:18,040
and reapproximate the artery ends?

277
00:11:18,510 --> 00:11:19,210
Great.

278
00:11:19,990 --> 00:11:21,460
Except the wall is inherently weakened.

279
00:11:21,460 --> 00:11:23,560
How long do you think it'll take to dilate again?

280
00:11:25,890 --> 00:11:27,320
It was nice while it lasted.

281
00:11:29,840 --> 00:11:31,130
I'll let Andrews know.

282
00:11:35,210 --> 00:11:37,970
I didn't want to say anything, I'm not entirely sure,

283
00:11:37,980 --> 00:11:41,090
but you suggested resecting the dilated tissue.

284
00:11:41,090 --> 00:11:43,480
What if we resect the entire abnormal segment,

285
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:44,510
shorten the ascending aorta...

286
00:11:44,510 --> 00:11:46,610
You were very right not to be entirely sure.

287
00:11:46,610 --> 00:11:49,410
You need to have enough aorta to plug in the donor hear...

288
00:11:52,030 --> 00:11:55,100
Actually, a version of that could maybe work.

289
00:11:55,570 --> 00:11:57,490
We'd reduce the risk of the aortic aneurysm

290
00:11:57,490 --> 00:11:59,660
if we used a Teflon graft.

291
00:12:04,100 --> 00:12:05,100
I, um...

292
00:12:06,060 --> 00:12:07,540
I didn't know you lived in a tent.

293
00:12:07,690 --> 00:12:08,540
Yes.

294
00:12:08,570 --> 00:12:10,560
We got to travel lots.

295
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:13,450
We saw all of Natrona County, Wyoming.

